<subSubSection id="DAE5B69A5BEEC310948F1C3F7FC56B11" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" type="taxonomic notes">
<paragraph id="8CE99654489934CC59D7176C7DA79AD2" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Taxonomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DBA7261B338A757549D55F6EA1D45111" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
The presence of cordiform fruits is the most remarkable character to distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="A92B456505C5447D775C84FB10540564" authorityName="Huan C. Wang, Shao Y. Liu &amp; Z. T. Ren" authorityYear="2022" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hemilophia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Hemilophia cardiocarpa" order="Brassicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cardiocarpa">
<emphasis id="39F90DB722BC7896A89DFC49CF2C04F8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Hemilophia cardiocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other species of this genus. Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName id="B598B06649BE6909012B54560E2034B9" genus="H." lsidName="H. cardiocarpa" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="cardiocarpa">
<emphasis id="72164C85C91C973305DA7E619AE225DF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. cardiocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="CED349A7D29A094106A7A8B436BFEFC3" genus="H." lsidName="H. rockii" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="rockii">
<emphasis id="02A316D64389F7465439243562E61DB9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. rockii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DD5AEAEA0747D7713668D22A2B1B38B1" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Hemilophia rockii A acauline leaf showing adaxial face B cauline leaf showing abaxial face C a portion of infructescence D fruit." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.194.82737.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673787" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">4</figureCitation>
) in having a similar habit and sharing similar indumentum, leaf shape, as well as flower size and arrangement. Nevertheless, it clearly differs from the latter by its cauline leaves usually ovate, rarely obovate or oblong (vs. oblanceolate to narrowly elliptic, or rarely ovate in 
<taxonomicName id="BA5D3C1FB56BF5C33D0FAC1FC276EFD4" genus="H." lsidName="H. rockii" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="rockii">
<emphasis id="38F519206913757BD6B62F9A38CA9C49" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. rockii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), 5-8 mm (vs. 3-4 (6)) long, 2-4 mm (vs. 1-1.5 (3)) wide, racemes usually 5-13 (vs. 5-6) -flowered, pedicels of fruits shorter than or nearly equal to its leaflike bract (vs. significantly longer than leaflike bract) and fruit cordate (vs. spindle or narrowly oblong) in shape. 
<taxonomicName id="6474AEF220A77B4FABDD42D0864A218D" genus="H." lsidName="H. cardiocarpa" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="cardiocarpa">
<emphasis id="8F0179AA32E4491C79945FBE99899488" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. cardiocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also similar to the type species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName id="4F92A4A912E80894F9FDC6AD54EB0972" genus="H." lsidName="H. pulchella" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis id="E96216F13ED306D584E9241BB7990597" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. pulchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Franch., from which it is readily distinguished by the racemes usually 5-13-flowered (vs. 2-3-flowered in 
<taxonomicName id="538A878B956F358AA799726B0082BDAB" genus="H." lsidName="H. pulchella" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" rank="species" species="pulchella">
<emphasis id="C961CC69DDBFFDEC04EA77FF6A99A6CA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">H. pulchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and petals bluish-white to white (vs. pink), 4-7 mm (vs. 2.5-3.5 mm) long, 2-3.5 mm (vs. 1.5-2 mm) wide. Taxa of 
<taxonomicName id="7B70CFBCBA2A5EF7EB48AA141F940FFC" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Hemilophia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Hemilophia" order="Brassicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="49A2E53948A3F877FA6D7421BFD5CA0E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Hemilophia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished through the morphological characters presented in the following identification key modified from 
<bibRefCitation id="44763FD1B24F1171054DC96D722CFBD1" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428602000264" author="Al-Shehbaz, IA" journalOrPublisher="Adansonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" refId="B2" refString="Al-Shehbaz, IA, 2002. New combinations in Brassicaceae (Cruciferae): Draba serpens is a Hemilophia and D. williamsii is a Lepidostemon. Edinburgh Journal of Botany 59(03): 443-446. https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428602000264" title="New combinations in Brassicaceae (Cruciferae): Draba serpens is a Hemilophia and D. williamsii is a Lepidostemon. Edinburgh Journal of Botany 59 (03): 443 - 446." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0960428602000264" year="2002">Al-Shehbaz (2002</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="139C3D3413A632A0EE044CB153EB4553" author="Al-Shehbaz, IA" editor="Hong, DY" journalOrPublisher="30. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, and Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" pagination="1 - 595" refId="B4" refString="Al-Shehbaz, IA, 2015. Brassicaceae. In: Hong, DY, Ed., Flora of Pan-Himalaya vol. 30. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, and Science Press, Beijing: 1 - 595" title="Brassicaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of Pan-Himalaya vol." year="2015">2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
